The township is less than three hours from the Kenya-Ethiopia border at Moyale but it is more less hours through other illegal points along the porous border. 

Drug menace 

Majority of the residents are Rastafarians who according to their doctrine use the drug as a holy sacrament. 

Bhang is simply referred to as ganja within Shashamane and some residents have it on a large scale production. 

Despite being illegal in Ethiopia, ganja is quietly tolerated in Shashamane.  

A regular visitor to the township once told me, “It’s a holy sacrament. We use ganja instead of wine, but we are not arrogant about it despite one getting “high” after using.” 

It remains unclear if the Kenyan government has ever engaged their Ethiopian counterparts on dealing with the drug trafficking menace in the region. A growing community of young women are introducing their children to marijuana as a way of preventing and treating certain illnesses. There are a number of shops selling CBD oil, majority doing their business strictly online. Ministry also reports recovery of 533 patients, pushing total recoveries in the country to 94,183. What does Mr Kenyatta want to do with the immense powers he’s consolidating? Court says concept of succession is about generational transfer of wealth from parents to their children.